This level focuses on asymmetric encryption (aka public key cryptography) i.e the sender and receiver use two different keys (a public key and a private key).

Asymmetric cryptography is used for 2 purposes \-   
i) **Confidentiality** \- **Encryption** done by **public key**  
                               **Decryption** done by **private key**  
 **– Used for key distribution**   
ii) **Authentication \- Decryption** done by **public key**  
                                **Encryption** done by **private key**

**Some things to understand**  
IP address of our machine from our machine is always 127.0.0.1

Localhost is an IP address pointing to the machine you are currently working on, whereas ports are almost like "sub addresses" on the machine itself. So bandit14 is the user we are logged on with, and localhost in that instance means the machine where the user bandit14 exists, which will be a server somewhere in the world because that is where our commands are being executed (over SSH). So we are trying to send the password to port 30 000 which lives on the same machine that we are currently connected to (and logged in as bandit14).

Ports \- Any server machine makes its services available to the Internet using numbered ports, one for each service that is available on the server. When we open a new tab on our browser, we make a new connection from our port to some web server.

The way connect to servers is through the TCP (Transmission Control Protocol). TCP is the standard by which we can connect to ports so that our computers can communicate with each other.

Here we need to apply the principles the principles of port scanning.

**Port Scanning \-** Port scanning is a method of determining which ports on a network are open and could be receiving or sending data.A port scan is a common technique hackers use to discover open doors or weak points in a network.

The rsa file has the following permissions **\-rw-rw-r--**

The first rw indicates that the user who created it and can read and write the rsafile.  
The first rw indicates that groups can read and write the rsafile. **( We need to change this permission)**  
And the last r indicates that all users can read it.

To change permission I used the **chmod command.** 

**Command \- chmod 600 rsafile**

**(In chmod**  
 **read \= 4**  
 **Write \= 2**  
  **Execute \= 1**  
**None \= 0\)**

**This command enables the user who created the file to both read and write files while groups and other users can’t do anything with it.**

**Command \- cat /usr/bin/cronjob\_bandit24.sh**  
![][image64]

This is the result I got. The functions of the script are \-

* The output of **whoami** command is getting saved in a variable called **myname.**  
    
* A folder called **bandit24**  exists in the **/var/spool** directory. The working directory needs to be changed to this directory.  
    
* Then the statement "Executing and deleting all scripts in var/spool/$myname/foo:” is printed which means all the scripts in the folder /var/spool/bandit24 is being deleted.  
    
*  A for loop is iterated to check all the files in the directory (.\* : All files in current working directory) 

*  A check is made to see if the current selected file is called **.** or **..** if not then the rest of the code is executed. (**“.”** means current directory (bandit24) and **“..”** means the parent directory (spool))

* A check is done to see if the owner of the file is **“bandit23”** i.e who we currently are. If the owner of the file is bandit23, it executes a **timeout command** which executes the programs and sends the **KILL signal after 60 seconds** to delete the script.

So from this we understand that whatever file is saved in the folder “bandit24” gets executed and if the file was created by “bandit23” then after 60 seconds of execution the file is deleted. If we want the password for “bandit24” we need to write a script that will be executed from the bandit24 folder. The script that we write should get the password and save in a location that we can access (/tmp directory).

We use the **shebang(\#\!)** to start writing scripts. Since the language used in this script is bash, we type **/bin/bash.**

To read the password we use the cat command and the password is located in /etc/bandit\_pass/bandit24 and we redirect it to our /tmp directory.

![][image67]

We use ctrl+X to exit and it will ask to save the file for which we answer “Y” for yes.

I used the ls command with the l flag to check the permission of my /tmp folder and found that there were executable permissions.

**Command \- ls \- l suvanscript.sh**

**![][image68]**

To change it into a read, write and executable format, I used the chmod command with 777\.

I used the ls \-l command again to view the updated permissions.

![][image69]

![][image70]

**Bandit 24 to 25**  
A daemon is listening on port 30002 and will give you the password for bandit25 if given the password for bandit24 and a secret numeric 4-digit pincode. There is no way to retrieve the pincode except by going through all of the 10000 combinations, called brute-forcing.

To log in to the port, I used the **netcat(nc) command** on port 30002\. If we are able to authenticate yourself and submit to the service the password for bandit24 we will be given password for bandit25.

![][image71]

Then it asks us to enter the password of bandit24 and a four digit secret pin code along with it.To find the pin we need to brute force it. Brute force is the process of trying out all the possible combinations until we reach the correct combination.

However manually inputting all the possible pin codes would be very time consuming process.Hence, we need to automate this process.

To automate this process we use a for loop which iterates from 0000 all the way till 9999.We use the echo command to copy the password of bandit24 and send the output to localhost port 30002\.

**Command \- for i in {0000..9999}; do echo (//password of bandit24) $i; done | nc localhost 30002**

![][image72]

This then automatically runs the brute force till we get the right pin for the password of bandit25.

![][image73]   
![][image74]

**Password \- iCi86ttT4KSNe1armKiwbQNmB3YJP3q4**

**Bandit 25 to 26**  
**[🔐 Bandit Level 25-26 CTF Wargame Walkthrough | OverTheWire.org](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8XRavGM4-fA)**

 The shell for user bandit26 is not /bin/bash, but something else. We need to find out what it is, how it works and how to break out of it.

I used the ls command to see all the files listed in the directory and I saw there is a file  
called **bandit26.sshkey**.

I used the ssh command with \-i flag(identifier) to login to bandit26.However, when I tried to login to bandit26, I was temporarily logged in to bandit26 but I was logged out immediately.

**Command \- ssh \-i bandit26.sshkey-p2220 \-l bandit26 bandit.labs .overthewire.org**

**![][image75]**  
**![][image76]**

The question states that the default shell is not “/bin/bash”, so we need to find out what shell is being used.

I used the cat command on the /etc/passwd file. The “/etc/passwd” file consist of information regarding the users on the device along with the shell that is being used by each user.

![][image77]  
![][image78]

To get only the details of bandit26, I used the grep command.

**Command \- cat /etc/passwd | grep bandit26**  
**![][image79]**  
From this I found out that the the shell is **/usr/bin/showtext.**

I used the cat command to find out what this script is doing.  
![][image80]  
Looking at the content we see that the shell is an shell script that is using the “more” command and outputting the contents of the text.txt file and then terminating.The reason we were getting logged out is due to the line “exit 0” which is executed as soon as all the text from the txt.file is displayed

![][image81]

**![][image82]**

![][image83]
